ces how alternative food movements are affected by global and local trends. He covers a wide range of topics, including the ethos of halutzim ("pioneers," Zionist ideological farmers and workers), the utopian visions of the Israeli kibbutz, indigeneity that is claimed both by Palestinians and Jewish settlers in the Gaza Strip and in the West Bank, biblical meanings that have been ascribed to environmental and countercultural ideas, the Americanization of Israeli society, and its neoliberalized economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aNatural foodsxPolitical aspectszIsrael. 0aNatural foodsxSocial aspectszIsrael. 0aOrganic farmingxPolitical aspectszIsrael. 0aOrganic farmingxSocial aspectszIsrael. 4aArea Studies : Israel Studies. 4aBusiness and Economics : Agricultural Economics. 4aCultural Studies : Food. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848157940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438481579423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438481579/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles